03832nam a22004935i 9780804766654DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20221988cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047666547 a10.1515/97808047666542doi  a(DE-B1597)581893  a(OCoLC)1312726158  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aHIS0080002bisacsh1 aShue, Vivienne, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Reach of the State :bSketches of the Chinese Body Politic /cVivienne Shue. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4c©1988  a1 online resource (192 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tOne. State, society and politics under Mao: theory and irony in the study of contemporary China -- tTwo. Peasant Localism and the Chinese state: A center-periphery approach to the evolution of state socialism under Mao -- tThree. The Reach of the state: A comparative-historical approach to the "modernization" of local government in China -- tFour. Honeycomb and web: the process of change in rural China -- tNotes0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThese four conceptual and critical essays on state and society in contemporary China argue vigorously against the grain of prevailing scholarly interpretation. In substantive content, they explore two major themes from different historical and theoretical points of departure. First, the author argues that the party/state under Mao fell far short of the full control over China's peasant society that outside observers often assumed it had achieved. She shows, instead, how the Maoist state frequently pursued policies that in fact had the ironic effect of strengthening the resistance of rural communities against the central political apparatus. Second, she contends that once the true limitations on the Maoist state's power in rural areas are rightly understood, it becomes clear that one effect of the post-Mao economic and political reforms may be to enhance rather than to diminish the state's authority in the countryside — despite all the reformists' rhetoric to the contrary. These essays on "how to think about the Chinese state" are designed to stimulate debate about assumptions and methods in the field of Chinese political analysis. The controversies they raise, however, make them highly relevant to scholars outside Chinese studies who are interested in theories of the state, in the interrelations of state and society, and in the fate of the peasantry under socialism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 4aHistory -- Asian. 4aPolitics -- Asia. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z97831107042110 cprintz978080471458740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080476665440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804766654423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804766654/original  a978-3-11-070421-1  Stanford University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles